        Official Singles Chart on 10/6/2022

        10 June 2022 - 16 June 2022

        The Official UK Singles Chart reflects the UKs biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1 and MTV, the Top 100 is published exclusively on OfficialCharts.com. View the biggest songs of 2024 so far.

        Velvet Android

        12th June 2022
        3
        Vote score

        Agreed. Back in the old Guinness British Hit Singles books, a reissue or remix (as opposed to a single just re-entering the charts for a week or three during its original run) would be granted a separate listing to distinguish the separate chart feats, which always felt right.

        Since in most cases there's no such thing as a 'reissue' per se these days, given that any song available to stream can simply arrive back in the chart under its own steam, so to speak, it's admittedly harder to know how to approach this. I mean, I'm instinctively against letting the established history of, for instance, Running Up That Hill's no.3 sales peak from 1985 be overwritten by a quirk of the 2020s charts yet I can't really say how 'logical' that feeling is. Should there be some sort of statute of limitations on how old or how recent the prior chart appearance should be, in order to be (in)eligible for rewriting in the manner? I don't know how or where you'd draw the line, of course.

        But there certainly doesn't seem to be a huge amount of sense or consistency in the OCC's listings in this regard, for either singles or albums. Sometimes a modern-day chart reappearance of a song/album gets tacked onto the end of a decades-old chart run, sometimes it gets given a whole new listing, with no great apparent logic for the choice. Take for instance the famous weekly Elvis reissue programme of 2005, where all his old number 1s' new chart entries are (correctly) given new listings... except for the last, A Little Less Conversation, where it's tacked onto that song's original 2002 chart run even though its 2005 reappearance was a limited-edition reissue just as all the preceding 17 singles had been.

        In some cases, these things appear to be affected by what record label things reappeared on. Sometimes it's just obviously a result of a misspelling causing a separate entry (e.g. a song called What Do Ya Say being entered into the database on a later occasion as What Do You Say), 'creating' a whole new hit where none existed. Sometimes there appears to be no such reason so I can only assume the person typing the info in was simply oblivious to a song/album's past chart life or to whatever the guidelines are, if they indeed exist...
